# ROS2 Development Rules

## General Guidelines
- Always follow official ROS2 coding standards and best practices
- Use ament_cmake as build system and colcon as build tool
- Prioritize rclcpp and rclpy for C++ and Python development
- Ensure code readability and maintainability

## Package Structure Standards
- Every ROS2 package must include package.xml and CMakeLists.txt (C++) or setup.py (Python)
- Source files go in src/ directory
- Header files go in include/package_name/ directory
- Launch files go in launch/ directory
- Configuration files go in config/ directory
- URDF/Xacro files go in urdf/ directory

## C++ Coding Standards
- Use modern C++ standards (C++17 or higher)
- Class names use PascalCase, functions and variables use snake_case
- All ROS2 nodes should inherit from rclcpp::Node
- Use smart pointers for memory management, avoid raw pointers
- Initialize all ROS2 objects (publishers, subscribers, services) in constructor
- Use rclcpp::spin() or executors to manage node lifecycle

## Python Coding Standards
- Follow PEP 8 coding style
- Class names use PascalCase, functions and variables use snake_case
- All ROS2 nodes should inherit from rclpy.node.Node
- Initialize all ROS2 objects in __init__ method
- Use rclpy.spin() to manage node lifecycle
- Properly handle node shutdown and resource cleanup

## Message and Service Design
- Message definition files go in msg/ directory with .msg extension
- Service definition files go in srv/ directory with .srv extension
- Action definition files go in action/ directory with .action extension
- Field names use snake_case
- Add clear comments explaining message purpose

## Topic and Service Naming
- Use descriptive names in snake_case format
- Avoid abbreviations unless widely known
- Private topics use ~/ prefix
- Global topics use / prefix cautiously
- Service names should clearly express their functionality

## Launch File Standards
- Use Python launch files (.launch.py)
- Import necessary launch modules: LaunchDescription, Node, etc.
- Use parameterized configuration, avoid hardcoding
- Add appropriate comments and documentation
- Support parameter-based node configuration

## Parameter Management
- Use ROS2 parameter system for configuration management
- Declare all parameters in node constructor
- Provide reasonable default values
- Support parameter validation and range checking
- Parameter names use snake_case

## Error Handling and Logging
- Use ROS2 logging system: RCLCPP_INFO, RCLCPP_WARN, RCLCPP_ERROR, etc.
- For Python use: self.get_logger().info(), warn(), error(), etc.
- Use appropriate log levels reasonably
- Add error checking at critical operations
- Provide meaningful error messages

## CMakeLists.txt Best Practices
- Specify appropriate CMAKE_MINIMUM_REQUIRED version
- Use find_package to find all dependencies
- Configure ament_target_dependencies correctly
- Use install() commands to install all necessary files
- Add appropriate compilation options and warnings

## Testing Standards
- Write unit tests for all nodes
- Use gtest (C++) or pytest (Python)
- Test files go in test/ directory
- Configure test targets in CMakeLists.txt
- Ensure tests can run independently

## Documentation and Comments
- Add documentation comments for all public interfaces
- Use Doxygen format (C++) or docstrings (Python)
- README.md should include package purpose, dependencies, and usage
- Add inline comments for complex algorithms and business logic

## Dependency Management
- Correctly declare all dependencies in package.xml
- Distinguish between build_depend, exec_depend, and test_depend
- Avoid unnecessary dependencies
- Use rosdep for system dependency management

## Code Quality
- Use static analysis tools to check code quality
- Perform regular code refactoring
- Follow DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) principle
- Maintain single responsibility for functions and classes

## Performance Considerations
- Avoid time-consuming operations in callback functions
- Set appropriate queue depths and QoS configurations
- Use appropriate timer frequencies
- Consider memory usage and CPU consumption

When writing ROS2 code, please follow the above rules to ensure code quality, maintainability, and good compatibility with the ROS2 ecosystem.